<CLR_EXEC>.clarification_question: explain how integrated gradients work in very simple terms

<CLR_EXEC>.llm_response: Integrated Gradients is a technique used to explain the predictions of AI models. It works by analyzing the importance of each feature in the input data. Imagine you have an image, and you want to know which parts of it are most important for the AI's decision. Integrated Gradients gradually changes the image from a baseline (like a completely black image) to the actual image, calculating the contribution of each pixel to the prediction. This helps highlight which areas of the image are most influential in the AI's decision-making process. In the ISee Platform, you can explore similar gradient-based techniques such as '/Images/GradientInput', which computes attributions by taking the partial derivatives of the output with respect to the input and multiplying them with the input itself. This method is designed to improve the sharpness of attribution maps. Additionally, methods like '/Images/SmoothGrad' and '/Images/VarGrad' offer enhancements by averaging gradients or their variance over small perturbations, reducing visual noise and improving explanation clarity. These explainers are available for you to try out and gain deeper insights into model predictions.
